05449nam a22008055i 9783112209011DE-B159720230228020105.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831122090117 a10.1515/97831122090112doi  a(DE-B1597)566630  a(OCoLC)1197553306  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aV46 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a387.50142221 aShafiq, Suhanna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSeafarers of the Seven Seas :bThe Maritime Culture in the Kitab 'Aja'ib al-Hind by Buzurg Ibn Shahriyar (d. 399/1009) /cSuhanna Shafiq. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (181 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIslamkundliche Untersuchungen ,x0939-1940 ;v31100tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbstract -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Figures, Tables and Maps -- tAbbreviations and Symbols -- tLibrary of Congress Arabic Transliteration System -- tChapter 1: Introduction -- tChapter 2: Literature Review -- tChapter 3: Buzurg ibn Shahriyār: A Historical and Geographical Perspective -- tChapter 4: The Sea Stories of Buzurg ibn Shahriyār -- tChapter 5: Life at Sea -- tChapter 6: Maritime Terminology in Buzurg’s Kitāb ʿAjāʾib al-Hind: An Investigative Analysis -- tChapter 7: Conclusion -- tAppendices -- tBibliography -- tIndex of places -- tIndex of General Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSeafaring is a particularly important aspect of Islamic history, as not only did it allow Muslims to spread Islam as far as the seas of China, but it also played a huge role in the trade and commerce of the Indian Ocean. Yet, despite the importance of this aspect of Arabian and Islamic history, few studies have been carried out regarding the socio-cultural maritime history and the literature of the period. Even fewer deal with the language of maritime material culture. The study is a synchronic investigation into medieval maritime terminology as found in Buzurg ibn Shahriyar’s Kitab 'Aja’ib al-Hind, the etymology of the nomenclature, as well as a diachronic inquiry to establish if there is a continuity of its use from the classical and medieval period to present times. It considers what the best source is for the study of maritime culture; whether lexicographical works provide us with the information we need, or whether Arabic literary sources provide more valuable information in this respect. So the work leads to a better understanding of the terminology both in definition, and in the historical, geographical, cultural and religious context in which it was used. Alongside the analysis of the maritime terminology of third-fourth/ninth-tenth century, the study ascertains how much information can be extracted from the sources regarding the evolution or development of Arabian-Persian-Indian seafaring in the Indian Ocean from early Islam to the coming of the Portuguese in the fifteenth century.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aNaval art and sciencevTerminologyxArabic. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG0 cprintz978387997424540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783